== Audit Log Schema

Every safety decision is logged with: timestamp, session ID, user ID, event type (`recommendation_filtered`, `allergen_block`, `preference_change`, `circuit_breaker`, `injection_detected`), decision (allow/deny/escalate), context (input, allergen profile, matched allergen, confidence), reason, and outcome.

= Architecture Diagram

The three-rail architecture is visualized in the companion SVG file (`safety-architecture.svg`), showing:

+ *Input Rails* (red): OCR -> Injection Detection -> Schema Validation -> PII Scanner
+ *Execution Rails* (amber): LLM Engine -> Circuit Breaker -> Hallucination Check -> Cross-Contamination Warning
+ *Output Rails* (green): *Allergen Hard Filter* -> Confidence Scorer -> Health Claim Filter -> Disclaimer Engine
+ *Support Systems*: Allergen Profile DB, Audit Log, Human Ops escalation
+ *Circuit Breaker State Machine*: CLOSED -> OPEN -> HALF-OPEN -> CLOSED

The allergen filter (output rail) has a direct, non-bypassable connection to the User Allergen Profile DB.

= Conclusions and Recommendations

+ *Deploy allergen filtering as a code-level post-filter* — not an LLM prompt. This is the single most important safety decision.
+ *Use NeMo-style three-rail architecture* with mechanical (fast, reliable) + cognitive (flexible) detection at each rail.
+ *Fail-closed on all safety-related service failures.* An allergy user receiving no recommendation is infinitely safer than receiving a wrong one.
+ *Audit every safety decision.* Regulators and liability lawyers will ask for this.
+ *Require explicit confirmation for allergen profile changes.* Memory poisoning + social engineering must not silently remove an allergy.
+ *Add cross-contamination disclaimers* for all allergy users, regardless of specific dish ingredients — shared kitchens are a real risk.

